main event: On July 23, 1956, in Hollywood, California, an observer reported a fast-moving, green, circular object at an altitude of approximately 20,000 feet. The observation lasted for about 3 seconds.
interesting points: The object was described as circular, the size of a dime, and light green in color, moving very fast at high altitude.
The observation was made under clear and balmy conditions with good visibility, and the wind at 20,000 feet was estimated to be 13 knots.
The report suggests that the observer was scanning for aircraft and the object was out of visual sight after 35 seconds.
The conclusion drawn in the report was that the sighting was likely an astronomical phenomenon, specifically a meteor.
The observer's location was given as Hollywood, California, and the entire observation lasted only 3 seconds.
